            <h2>6.1 The Italian Game (1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4)</h2>
            <p>The Italian Game is one of the oldest and most instructive openings in chess. By placing the bishop on <code>c4</code>, White immediately targets Black’s weakest point: the <code>f7</code> pawn, which is defended only by the Black King.</p>
            
            <h3>The Classical Approach (Giuoco Piano: 3...Bc5 4.c3)</h3>
            <p>White intends to build a classical pawn center with a quick <code>d4</code>. If Black plays passively, White wins space and restricts Black's piece mobility. If Black counterattacks with <code>4...Nf6</code>, White must be prepared to protect or sacrifice the center dynamically.</p>

            <div class="highlight-box pro-tip">
                <h4>The Evans Gambit (4.b4!?)</h4>
                <p>For aggressive players, the Evans Gambit offers a high-win-rate alternative. White sacrifices a wing pawn to draw the Black bishop out of position, gaining vital tempos with <code>c3</code> and <code>d4</code> to build an overwhelming attacking initiative against the uncastled king.</p>
            </div>

            <h2>6.2 The Ruy Lopez (1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5)</h2>
            <p>Considered the gold standard of open games, the Ruy Lopez exerts subtle, long-term strategic pressure. Instead of aiming directly at <code>f7</code>, the bishop on <code>b5</code> attacks the defender of the <code>e5</code> pawn.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Mainlines (3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.O-O):</strong> White maintains tactical tension, planning to slowly build an optimal center while retaining the bishop pair.</li>
                <li><strong>The Exchange Variation (3...a6 4.Bxc6 dxc6):</strong> White damages Black's pawn structure immediately. While Black gets the compensation of the bishop pair, White aims for a simplified endgame where their healthy kingside pawn majority can easily create a passed pawn.</li>
            </ul>
        </article>


