            <h2>7.1 The Queen's Gambit (1.d4 d5 2.c4)</h2>
            <p>Unlike the King's Gambit, the Queen's Gambit is highly stable and strategically sound. White offers a flank pawn to tempt Black's center pawn away from <code>d5</code>, allowing White to take total control of the central squares.</p>
            
            <h3>Queen's Gambit Accepted (2...dxc4)</h3>
            <p>Black surrenders the center temporarily. White typically responds with <code>3.e3</code> or <code>3.e4</code>, rapidly reclaiming the pawn with the light-squared bishop while developing pieces naturally.</p>

            <h3>Queen's Gambit Declined (2...e6)</h3>
            <p>The most resilient defense. Black reinforces <code>d5</code>. White's main plan is to develop the knight to <code>c3</code>, pin the black knight with <code>Bg5</code>, and execute a central breakthrough or a minority pawn attack on the queenside.</p>

            <h2>7.2 The London System (1.d4 d5 2.Bf4)</h2>
            <p>The ultimate system-based opening. White uses a set layout regardless of what Black plays, making it highly reliable and low-risk.</p>
            <div class="highlight-box pro-tip">
                <h4>The Golden Triangle Setup</h4>
                <p>White places pawns on <code>d4</code>, <code>c3</code>, and <code>e3</code>, while developing the dark-squared bishop outside the pawn chain to <code>f4</code>. This creates an incredibly solid fortress that minimizes early blunders and guarantees an active middlegame plan focused on the <code>e5</code> square.</p>
            </div>
        </article>


