            <h2>8.1 The Sicilian Defense (1.e4 c5)</h2>
            <p>The most popular and aggressive response to <code>1.e4</code>. By playing <code>1...c5</code>, Black fights for the center asymmetricaly, avoiding the symmetric drawish tendencies of <code>1...e5</code>.</p>
            
            <h3>The Najdorf Variation (2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6)</h3>
            <p>The choice of world champions. The unassuming move <code>5...a6</code> stops all white pieces from utilizing the critical <code>b5</code> square, paving the way for a powerful counterattack on the queenside with <code>...b5</code> and <code>...Bb7</code>.</p>

            <h3>The Dragon Variation (5...g6)</h3>
            <p>Black fianchettoes the dark-squared bishop to <code>g7</code>, where it acts as a sniper down the long diagonal. This leads to razor-sharp, double-edged middlegames where king safety is paramount.</p>

            <h2>8.2 The Classical Open Game (1...e5)</h2>
            <p>A solid, reliable foundation for players who prefer open lines and direct development. If White enters the Italian or Ruy Lopez, Black uses precise defensive lines to neutralize White's temporary first-move initiative.</p>
        </article>


