            <h2>9.1 The King's Indian Defense (1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7)</h2>
            <p>A hypermodern defense where Black invites White to build a massive pawn center, intending to break it down later with counter-strikes like <code>...e5</code> or <code>...c5</code>.</p>
            <p>Middlegames in the King's Indian are highly thematic: White usually attacks on the queenside where they hold a space advantage, while Black launches a mating storm directly against White's king on the kingside using moves like <code>...f5</code> and <code>...g5</code>.</p>

            <h2>9.2 The Slav Defense (1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6)</h2>
            <p>The rock-solid option. Unlike the Queen's Gambit Declined (<code>2...e6</code>), the Slav Defense supports the central <code>d5</code> pawn with <code>2...c6</code>, keeping the diagonal open for Black's light-squared bishop to develop freely to <code>f5</code> or <code>g4</code>.</p>
            <div class="highlight-box pro-tip">
                <h4>The Structural Advantage</h4>
                <p>By keeping the light-squared bishop active outside the pawn chain, Black avoids the "problem child" bishop limitation that plagues many alternative closed systems.</p>
            </div>
        </article>


