            <h2>10.1 Refuting the Scholar's Mate (1.e4 e5 2.Qh5?!)</h2>
            <p>The most common amateur trap attempting an early mate on <code>f7</code>. Bringing the Queen out prematurely violates core opening principles. Black wins easily by remaining calm and developing with tempo:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>Protect the <code>e5</code> pawn first with <code>2...Nc6</code>.</li>
                <li>When White attacks <code>f7</code> with <code>3.Bc4</code>, block it with <code>3...g6</code>, attacking the queen.</li>
                <li>After White retreats with <code>4.Qf3</code> (renewing the threat), play <code>4...Nf6</code> to completely shut down the attack while developing a piece.</li>
            </ol>

            <h2>10.2 The Fried Liver Attack (1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4 Nf6 4.Ng5)</h2>
            <p>White targets the <code>f7</code> square aggressively with a knight and bishop. If Black defends poorly with <code>4...d5 5.exd5 Nxd5?</code>, White can execute a devastating knight sacrifice: <code>6.Nxf7! Kxf7 7.Qf3+</code>, dragging the black king into the open center.</p>

            <div class="highlight-box pro-tip">
                <h4>The Traxler Counterattack Option</h4>
                <p>Advanced players facing <code>4.Ng5</code> can shock White by ignoring the threat on <code>f7</code> entirely, counterattacking with <code>4...Bc5!?</code>. If White captures on <code>f7</code>, Black answers with a violent, sacrificial onslaught against White's own king.</p>
            </div>
        </article>
